<br>
In defense of my fellow smiths - I snicker when I hear people talking about mastering baking or brewing in an evening for 20-30 PP.  Getting to the level of skill to make FP armor takes well over 1K of platinum for most folks unless they're attempting it at higher levels with good stat-boosting gear, and friends to buff their strength to god-like levels.  It also takes a lot of time - we're talking a played day or more.  That's just to get to the level where it is viable (175), and you still have a good chance at failing on the 3-sheet items.<br>
<br>
Oh, can't forget the cost of leather padding... I pay aspiring tailors 80-100 PP per stack of padding, and each armor combine requires one padding.  Or I can blow more playing time camping spiderlings, wolves &amp; such and make'em myself... you get the idea.<br>
<br>
With the cost per attempt at making each piece of FP armor being about 30-100 PP... the smith who is charging you 75-100 PP per sheet to make the item is accounting for the chance of failure, especially on the 3-sheet items.  (Heck, folded MQ sheets trivial well below 176, and I still fail on that occasionally - 23 PP down the oubilette there!)  He/she WILL go broke if trying to do it consistently for 10 PP per AC, which some smiths who seem to be poor at math are charging.<br>
<br>
There is also a time investment - molds and metal are available in a limited number of places.  For example, your options for small plate molds are Neriak and Kaladim - with MQ metal avaialble in Steamfont or Highkeep - you get the idea.<br>
<br>
Look at it this way - you can pay the smith his price, or spend the same amount of money and throw away all your EQ time for a week or so skilling up, which is what WE have done.  You're trading plat for time, friend.  <br>
<br>
Or - YOU go get all the materials and bring them to the smith, and accept the cost of failures yourself.  Any smith at this level will likely say &quot;Sure!&quot; if you make this offer, you're effectively subsidizing a run of skill attempts for him/her.<br>
<br>
Don't even get me started on dyes - I made a brief stab at collecting them myself, gave up and started buying it.  Have to hunt SOMETIME, hehe. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   (Oh, Shalindar, I stil owe your for those components!  D'oh!  Saturday, dear.)<br>
<br>
IMNSHO, the only people who have it tougher than smiths in this regard are jewellers, and to some extent tailors.  Jewelcraft is EXPENSIVE, even by the standards of smithing, and the time investment seems to be at least the same if not greater.  Tailoring requires the camping of critters for components, which is a HUGE time sink, and until the discovery of the Wu's Fighting Armor recipies recently the path to skilling up to the Velious tailoring seemed bleak indeed.<br>
<br>
Sorry for the rant - don't get me wrong, I LOVE being able to make this stuff.  I'm assuming the person complaining about the cost of smithed gear was unaware of the reasons behind the pricing, so my goal was to educate. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Hope this has shed some light on the subject.<br>
<br>
