<br>
Well, to take it from a tailoring side, I would have to say that smithing does have a couple of advantages over tailoring.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Mind you, this isn't to say that Amergen is wrong, just that smithing as a skill does have some serious bonuses over tailoring... from this players sewing experience.<br>
<br>
1) You can BUY pretty much all your raw materials (molds, metals, etc.)  Tailors can make money from the get go (costs 5 gold for a pattern, but can sell the finished patchwork-leather item back for 6 gold); but have to go hunting for silks, pelts, threads, etc... not to even mention trying to get a smith to make you a stack of metal studs, or a brewer to make some heady kiola to you.  So, technically, if you want to be a &quot;solo tailor&quot; you'll need to have smithing in the 40s or so (for the metal studs), and brewing of about 70 (for the Kiola)... but then you need the viscus mana, and this isn't even thinking about reinforced leather either.<br>
<br>
You want to know why my tailoring is only a 60?  I haven't been able to brew any heady kiola for myself, and, few offer it in an auction.  I've done my best to make shaman bags, but grizzly skins are a bear to find, and you need at least six spiderling skils to make the silk cord for the shaman bag.  Talk about a big-pain-in the behind!<br>
<br>
2) Few to none ask for leather armor; you do get some tells for raw silk, and the rare requrest for studded leather; however, for a long time, you're only recourse is to take your finished product, and sell it back to the merchant.  You only start being able to sell to others when you start to be able to make cured silk and tailored quivers/backpacks (which start in the upper fifties range.)  So, most &quot;tailors&quot; pewter out in the teens... if that.  Most smiths pewter out in the 80s or so (when they can sell/make banded.)<br>
<br>
So... when new tailors see all the requests for &quot;banded this&quot; and &quot;banded that&quot; it does get a bit depressing and your leather doesn't do much, except go back to the merchant.<br>
<br>
3) Time... I'd still have to give to smiths.  Ever try to camp crag spiders for silk swatches?  Or spiderlings for silk threads?  It's soooooooo time consuming.  Well... then again, you all have to run around a lot so... maybe we're even.  But then again, we have to brew for Heady Kiola, and smith for metal studs... so... maybe tailors have it a bit worse.<br>
<br>
4) Money.  What with all the new velious stuff, the price of silk swatches and threads is ridiculus now.  Especially if you don't have Mr. Uber Level to give your aspiring tailor a healthy hunk of change.  Honestly, I cannot afford to give the 30 - 50 plat for a stack of swatches, and the 20 plat for a stack of threads... which leaves me to either hunting them myself... or to despirately try to buy them off merchants, or players who don't ask absorbant prices for them.<br>
<br>
Just some quick thoughts from a tailor who so wants to start making some real stuff... just need to go hunting the raw components.<br>
<br>
Donnalinna<br>
